1.Difference between deep copy and shallow copy. 
ANS :
	Shallow Copy
	- Copies object reference.
	- Both objects point to same memory.
	- Changes in one object affect the other.
	- Default clone() does shallow copy.

	Deep Copy
	- Copies actual object data.
	- New object is created with separate memory.
	- Changes in one object do NOT affect the other
2 What are varargs in Java? 5
ANS : 
	- Varargs means variable-length arguments.
	- Allows method to accept any number of arguments.
	- Internally treated as array.
	
	Short Example
	class Demo {
	    static void add(int... numbers) {
	        int sum = 0;
	        for(int n : numbers) {
	            sum += n;
	        }
	        System.out.println("Sum = " + sum);
	    }
	
	    public static void main(String[] args) {
	        add(10, 20);
	        add(5, 10, 15);
	    }
	}
	
3 What is autoboxing and unboxing? 
ANS :
	Autoboxing
	- Converting primitive → Wrapper object automatically.
	- int → Integer

	Unboxing
	- Converting Wrapper → primitive automatically.
	- Integer → int
	
		public class Demo {
	    public static void main(String[] args) {
	
	        int a = 10;
	
	        Integer obj = a;   // Autoboxing
	        int b = obj;       // Unboxing
	
	        System.out.println(b);
	    }
	}
	
4 What are the differences between == and equals() for Strings?
ANS :
	1. == Operator
		String s1 = "Java";
		String s2 = "Java";
		
		System.out.println(s1 == s2);  // true
	
	- It compares memory reference (address).
	- Checks whether two references point to the same object in memory.
	- Does NOT compare actual content.
	- Works for all objects.
	
		Example 1 (Using new keyword)
		String s1 = new String("Java");
		String s2 = new String("Java");
		System.out.println(s1 == s2);  // false
	
2. equals() Method
ANS : 
	- Defined in Object class.
	- In String class, it is overridden.
	- Compares actual content (character by character).
	- Returns true if content is same.
	
		Example
		String s1 = new String("Java");
		String s2 = new String("Java");
		
		System.out.println(s1.equals(s2));  // true

5 Explain String concatenation and interning.
ANS :
	String Concatenation :
	- String concatenation means joining two or more strings into one.
	- It can be done using + operator or concat() method.
	- Since String is immutable, every concatenation creates a new object.
	- For multiple concatenations, StringBuilder is preferred for better performance.
	
		Example:
		String s1 = "Hello";
		String s2 = "World";
		String s3 = s1 + s2;
		System.out.println(s3);   // HelloWorld
	
	String Interning :
	
	- String interning is the process of storing string literals in the String Constant Pool (SCP) to avoid duplicate objects and save memory.
	- If the same string literal already exists in SCP, Java reuses that object instead of creating a new one.
	
		Example:
		String s1 = "Java";
		String s2 = "Java";
		System.out.println(s1 == s2);  // true (same SCP reference)

	- If we use new keyword, object is created in heap:
		String s3 = new String("Java");
		System.out.println(s1 == s3);  // false
	- We can use intern() method to move string to SCP.
	
	
	
